ownedComment.body:
Use Case: Estimating effort with COCOMO Early Design Model
Primary Course: 1. The project manager lands on the decision factors page. 2. The system presents the tab for inputting decision factors. 3. The project manager specifies the decision factors for the project and click "next button" 4. The system presents the tab for inputting scale factors. 5. The project manager specifies the values for scale factors and click the "next" button 6. The system presents the tab for inputting early design model's cost drivers. 7. The project manager specifies the values for the cost drivers and click "next" button. 8. The system presents the tab for inputting the project sizes. 9. The project manager input the values for the project sizes and click "estimate effort" button. 10. The system presents the tab for a summary of the estimated effort. 11. The project manager views the estimation result and click "start process" to initiate an instance of the recommended process.
Alternative Courses: 5A1: The project manager wants to go back to modify the project decision factors. 1. The project manager click "prev" button. 2. The system presents the tab for specifying the decision factors. 3. The project manager modifies the values of decision factors.
7A1: The project manager wants to go back to modify the scale factors. 1. The project manager click "prev" button. 2. The system presents the tab for specifying the scale factors. 3. The project manager modifies the values of the scale factors.
9A1: The project manager wants to go back to modify the cost drivers. 1. The project manager click "prev" button. 2. The system presents the tab for specifying the cost drivers. 3. The project manager modifies the values of the cost drivers. 10A1: The project manager wants to view detailed report of the estimation results. 1. The project manager click "detailed results" tab. 2. The system presents the tab for detailed effort estimation results. 10A2: The project manager wants to adjust the factors after viewing the estimation result. 1. The project manager click "Prev" button. 2. The system presents the tab for specifying the project sizes.

This package contains use cases which define how an Actor will interact with the proposed system.
Each interaction may be specified using scenarios, sequence diagrams, communication diagrams and other dynamic diagrams or textual descriptions which together describe how the system, when viewed as a "black-box", interacts with a user.

Actors are the users of the system being modeled. Each Actor will have a well-defined role, and in the context of that role have useful interactions with the system.
A person may perform the role of more than one Actor, although they will only assume one role during one use case interaction.
An Actor role may be performed by a non-human system, such as another computer program.
The System Boundary shows the logical interface between users and the system being described.
